          "title": "The invocation that reverses the world's order (vv. 1-6)",
          "body": "The psalm opens with a direct command: 'Let God arise.' The line echoes Numbers 10:35, the words Moses spoke whenever the ark set out on the march — 'Arise, O Lord, and let Your enemies be scattered.' The liturgical procession being narrated in Psalm 68 is thus immediately situated within the Mosaic wilderness tradition. The Divine Warrior's arising does not merely defeat enemies; it simultaneously reverses every form of social deprivation. Verses 5-6 are among the most concentrated social-theology statements in the Psalter: God is father of the fatherless, judge for widows, home-maker for the lonely, liberator of prisoners. These are not separate acts of charity appended to the warfare theme — they are consequences of the same divine arising. When God stands up, enemies scatter AND orphans receive a father. The one reversal is the other side of the other. The only exception to this comprehensive restoration is the 'rebellious,' who dwell in a parched land (v. 6) — the psalm's first use of *sarar*, 'stubborn resisters,' who will reappear at verse 18."
